The Blonde Eve
I. The Apparition

You really did look like Eve, the blonde Eve
in the older paintings, when the old haunted
door swung open and you stood there, created
or just now delivered into the room.
How was it that you glowed so much, with that
perfect musculature, that fresh enthusiasm,
and the callus on your hand like proof
that Eden also had its work to do?
It felt as if you had just come out of Eden,
or maybe that apartment had become Eden
because you entered it. I shook your hand.
You were a gift from the gods. No other
explanation has improved in thirty-two years.
You had the sunlit look of first arrival.

II. The Wrong Name

They said you were a lesbian, and this
was wonderful, they said, because they wanted
the world depopulated. That was the mood
inside the room: the sterile little triumph
of category over flesh. But you
wanted to have a child. That was the kind
of lesbian you were. The wrong word broke
against the fact of you the next night.
So everything acquired an erotic edge.
You had found a man who said he meant
to solve the problem of Nuclear Weapons Corpus,
and whom the girls inside the apartment called
a genius, who was looking for the girl
at the end of the world. The actual girl.

III. Outer Limits

You looked like two different women stitched
together, but the seam was beautiful.
Your skull was Outer Limits range, just pushing it,
but it still radiated beauty.
It carried the human shape farther out,
toward the edge where beauty enters alien law
and comes back as beauty, only more so.
I saw things happening in your eyes I had
never seen before: a sky-blue line
forming, advancing inward toward the iris,
holding before the deep earth blue, yet always
advancing. It seemed martial in an earthly way,
as if the eye itself had taken ground.

IV. No Conventional History

No wonder I forgot you. You were so
different. Where would you fit into any
conventional history? Did you have a past?
I feel you had been created somewhere close
in the timeline, or had just emerged there
in the city before you went to try
to be “the roommate.” Did anyone know
anything about you? To this day,
thirty-two years later, no one has given me
a single detail: where you came from, what
happened, who you were before the door.
They knew one thing: that you were a lesbian.
Even that failed the next night, when you tried
to get me to follow. Then you were gone.

V. The Sclera

But still the final image keeps returning:
your sclera whiter than white, like certain
perfect clouds suspended in the sun.
Cloud-white, almost weatherless, as if
some other sky had entered through your eyes
and left its evidence around the blue.
The old door opened. Eden entered. Then
the city closed around you like a book
with all its pages sealed against the room.
Thirty-two years later, still I have
the fact of whiteness in the sun,
and you, impossible to place in time,
standing there, newly made, trying to begin.
